From: Matthew Jackson <matthew@pq.io>
Subject: [PATCH 4/9] hw/display/apple-gfx-linux: display callbacks and
 console integration

Implement the five display callbacks libapplegfx invokes,
plus the frame-readback bottom half that pushes rendered
frames into QEMU's DisplaySurface:

  * `apple_gfx_frame_ready`     - increments the pending-frames
    counter (capped at 2 to bound BH queue growth on a runaway
    renderer) and schedules the drain bottom half. Thread-safe
    via `qatomic_*`; the library's render thread and the
    BQL-held drain BH both touch `pending_frames`.
  * `apple_gfx_frame_ready_bh`  - under the BQL, drains one
    pending token by calling `lagfx_display_read_frame` into
    `surface_data(s->surface)` and posts `dpy_gfx_update` when
    a new frame landed. `LAGFX_ERR_NO_FRAME` is treated as a
    silent no-op (the library's render pipeline may not have
    produced a frame yet); any other non-OK status is logged
    at `LOG_GUEST_ERROR`. The BH re-arms itself while more
    frames remain queued so the display stays current without
    stalling the renderer. Verifies stride parity between the
    library readback and QEMU's DisplaySurface; warns on
    mismatch.
  * `apple_gfx_mode_changed`    - swaps the QEMU display surface
    to the new (width, height).
  * `apple_gfx_cursor_glyph`    - converts BGRA from the library
    to RGBA for QEMU's cursor, re-allocates via `cursor_alloc`,
    and calls `dpy_cursor_define`.
  * `apple_gfx_cursor_moved`    - reads the library-side cursor
    position and forwards via `dpy_mouse_set`.
  * `apple_gfx_cursor_show`     - latches show/hide state and
    refreshes position under the same BH.

Console init uses a minimal `GraphicHwOps` with
`gfx_update_async = true` and no synchronous `gfx_update`;
rendering is driven entirely from the frame-ready BH. The
surface stride is read via `surface_stride()` rather than
assumed-equal to `width*4` so non-1920x1080 modes (the
device's 1440x1080 and 1280x1024 entries) cannot tear on a
pitch mismatch.

The readback path has been exercised end-to-end against the
library's Vulkan render target + clear-colour pipeline
(`libapplegfx-vulkan` 8edc43c): the library produces a
rendered VkImage, copies it to a linear BGRA8 buffer, and
notifies via `frame_ready`; this BH then pushes the buffer
into the DisplaySurface. Library-level proof is the
`vulkan-render` test; the full path via a booted macOS
guest is gated on an out-of-tree first-pixel harness.
There is no reasonable in-tree unit test because it requires
a running QEMU with a live QemuConsole plus an initialised
`lagfx_display_t`.

